response_data.name: Tierra De Agua Ecohotel
response_data.description:
At Tierra de Agua, we left the city to disconnect from the daily routine and reconnect with the healing and revitalizing magic that nature offers.

In a magical place in the Colombian tropical humid forest, Cocorna-Antioquia, we have a spectacular bamboo infrastructure crossed by an exuberant ravine with crystal clear waters and bordered by an ancestral path of fifteen hundred years, built by the indigenous people who inhabited the region. In addition, we have converted the cattle lands into a natural reserve of native forest in recovery, planted with organic cane with a panela sugar mill of 80 years of tradition and planted with coffee.

response_data.name: Raja Ampat Biodiversity Resort
response_data.description: Set in a remote prime spot, a secluded beach front location is where you find the tranquil Yenanas beach, nestled between jungle and ocean, is your escape to a place where family and friends come first. An exclusive natural compound designed to disconnect in Raja Ampat, but with all the modern conveniences blended with Papuan craftsmanship and warmth.

response_data.name: Maroochy Wetlands Sanctuary
response_data.description:
In the Maroochy Wetlands Sanctuary at Bli Bli, you can explore wet and dry eucalypt forests, rainforest, melaleuca forest, casuarina woodland, salt marsh and mangroves. You can watch over 200 different types of birds, as well as crabs, butterflies and other animals and organisms that make the wetlands their home, as detailed in the fauna and fungi species list[197KB].

Within this wetland, life thrives in land on the edge of the sea, flooded by freshwater and salty tides. One of south east Queensland's largest groups of Mangrove Ferns grow in these wetlands.

response_data.name: Cairns Botanic Gardens & Mount Whitfield Conservation Park
response_data.description: The Cairns Botanic Gardens is a tropical paradise, renowned as one of the best exhibitions of tropical plants in Australia. Come and explore the beauty of tropical plants, relax in stunning surroundings and learn about tropical flora and horticulture.

response_data.name: Fairmont Jasper Park Lodge
response_data.description: Set in the Canadian Rockies' largest national park, Fairmont Jasper Park Lodge has welcomed guests since the early 1900s. Our Main Lodge and rustic log cabins radiate out from the shores of Lac Beauvert, and you can enjoy breathtaking lake views from our modern Italian restaurant, lounge terrace and pool. Spot wildlife on nearby trails or relax in the spa. The all-season resort offers countless ways to connect with nature, from golfing on a course framed by majestic peaks to stargazing at our Planetarium.

Our tried-and-tested recipe for affordable accommodation really is hard to beat.

response_data.name: ibis Styles Tamworth
response_data.description: Newly refurbished in the heart of Tamworth. Located within walking distance to Tamworth's CBD, the Ibis Styles Tamworth provides 111 modernised guest rooms alongside an array of updated amenities. Providing extensive meeting facilities to accommodate everything from boardroom meetings to conferences, the hotel offers 24hr reception, free car parking, WIFI and a convenient guest laundry. Crossroads, the onsite restaurant and bar, is open 7 days a week serving breakfast, dinner and late night drinks.

response_data.name: Hôtel Mercure Rabat Sheherazade
response_data.description: The Mercure Rabat Sheherazade is an ideal location for exploring the treasures of the Moroccan capital. The Mausoleum of Mohammed V and Hassan Tower are 10 mins away. response_data.name: 80 Acres
response_data.description:
80 Acres is one of the few remaining large open spaces within metropolitan Adelaide that contains significant areas of remnant vegetation, high conservation plant species and a vast diversity of habitats. Traditionally owned by the Kaurna people, the area occupied by the park and its surrounds was used by Europeans as agricultural land during the 1830s. Informal walking trails run several directions through the park allowing access to its dense woodland. Many local species call this park home."
The attached image might work well for the banner for the Tangari Regional Reserve realm as it was taken within the reserve.

response_data.name: Tangari Park
response_data.description: Tangari Park contains approximately 60 hectares of natural vegetation. The area was traditionally owned by the Kaurna people. The area occupied by the park and its surrounds was used by Europeans as agricultural land during the 1830s. Today, it is one of the few remaining large open spaces within metropolitan Adelaide that contains significant areas of remnant vegetation, high conservation plant species and a vast diversity of habitats, and is an ideal location for birdwatchers.

response_data.name: Desert Botanical Garden in Phoenix, Arizona
response_data.description: When you think of a desert what springs to mind? For most of us sand and cacti are probably the first two things we think of. But what about colorful flowers, trees and bushes? What about swathes of lush, green plant life? These may not be what comes to mind when we think of deserts, but there is a wealth of plant life that thrives in desert conditions and it can be all of these things.

response_data.name: Presidio of San Francisco
response_data.description: Located at the Golden Gate, the Presidio is a national park site like no other, with surprising adventures for everyone. Get away from it all on a trail and enjoy the view from a scenic overlook. Or grab a great meal, visit a museum, browse in a store, or rest your head in a historic lodge. There’s always something new to discover!

response_data.name: My Backyard Bounty
response_data.description: The residents only expected to find 250–300 species. When they informally surveyed ecologists at a conference, showing them a photo of the property and a map of its location, most guessed similar numbers. Within weeks, they shot past their initial biodiversity estimate. Within two months, they tripled it. By the end of the year, they had identified a staggering 1150 unique species, including 1034 animals (948 arthropods — insects and their relatives), 103 plants, and 13 fungi.
